  "A technique for finding dy/dx when y is not explicitly written as a function of x, using the chain rule on trig and other functions": "",
  "Implicit differentiation differentiates both sides of an equation with respect to x, treating y as a function of x. For sin(y) = x, differentiating gives cos(y) * dy/dx = 1, so dy/dx = 1/cos(y) = 1/sqrt(1-x^2).": "",
  "What is the squeeze theorem and how does it prove lim sin(x)/x = 1?": "",
  "It uses integration to compute the limit in most standard conditions": "",
  "It uses L'Hopital's Rule, particularly regarding triangles according to conventional analysis": "",
  "It requires the Taylor series expansion according to conventional analysis": "",
  "If g(x) <= f(x) <= h(x) near a and lim g = lim h = L, then lim f = L. Applied with cos(x) <= sin(x)/x <= 1 near x = 0": "",
  "The squeeze theorem bounds sin(x)/x between cos(x) and 1 for small x (geometrically, using areas of triangles and a circular sector). Since both bounds approach 1, sin(x)/x must also approach 1.": "",
